Name: Illustrations of the IPA: American English: Southern Michigan
Comment:
Minimal pair examples from JIPA paper.
JIPA paper contained both a broad and narrow transcription. Broad transcription was used here.
There is no discussion of schwa in the JIPA paper. It has been added as an allophone to monophthongs,
in keeping with other analyses.

Contributor: Hayward, Katrina and Hayward, Richard J.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Arabic
Contributor: Thelwall, Robin and Sa{\textquotesingle}Adeddin, M. Akram
Comment:
The JIPA article does not specify whether geminate consonants are phonemic or not. Based
on the transcription it appears they are, and so the ones appearing in the transcription
have been treated as separate phonemes here.
In the JIPA article the geminate articles are written with a doubling of the conssonant
grapheme. Here I have use the length symbol, for consistency across languages.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Basaá
Contributor: Makasso, Emmanuel-Moselly and Lee, Seunghun J.
Comment:
High tone < ́>, low tone < ̀>, rising tone < ̌> and falling < ̂>
In the JIPA article prenasalised stops are indicated by a superscript homorganic
nasal preceding the voiced stop symbol. I was unable to replicate this, and so have
just used a superscript <n> preceding the stop.
Nasals can be syllabic, in which case they can take tone.
The click isn't mentioned in the text.
[r] isn't mentioned in the text. Because there are no instances of the voiced tap
in the transcript, it is assumed to represent this sound, either as the tap or an allophone
of it.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Belgian Limburg dialect of Hamont
Comment:
Superscript 1 refers to sleeptoon 'dragging tone' or Accent 1, and superscript 2 refers to stootoon 'push tone' or Accent 2.

I could not use superscript, and so have just placed the numerals '1' and '2' in normal font.

Minimal pairs and minimal pair examples from JIPA paper.

The glottal stop does not appear in the phoneme inventory, but a minimal pair containing it is provided, and it is discussed along with other consonant phonemes "Glottal stops are confined to the strong onset of word-initial vowels.

Here it has been included in the inventory.

[ɪː] is considered to be borrowed from standard Belgian Dutch, not a native vowel, but appears frequently in the text, and here has been included as a phoneme.

Vowel nasalisation is not discussed in the paper. The vowel [ɛ̃ː] has been added as an allophone of its non-nasalised counterpart.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Belgian Standard Dutch
Comment:
Many of the sounds presented in the consonant phoneme chart are considered to be the result of phonological
processes rather than phonemes. I have made a judgement call here on when to present them as phonemes, and when
to present them as allophones dependent on the information in the paper.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Cicipu
Comment:
Homorganic nasals are represented as allophones of /n/.
Tones are marked using diacritics: < ́> for high tone; < ̀> for low tone; < ̌> for HLH tone; < ̂ > for LHL tone.
Each tone variation for each vowel is written as an allophone of the vowel phonemes.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: The Dutch dialect of Weert
Illustrations of the IPA: Ega
Contributor: Connell, Bruce and Ahoua, Firmin and Gibbon, Dafydd
Comment:
"Ega is a register tone language with three basic level tones, High (H) [represented by diacritic ́ on vowels], Mid (M)
[represented by diacritic  ̄ on vowels] and Low (L) [represented by diacritic  ̀  on vowels]" p102
No mention was made in the discussion of vowel length, and so I have included long vowels as allophones.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Ersu
Contributor: Chirkova, Katia and Wang, Dehe and Chen, Yiya and Amelot, Angélique and Antolík, Tanja Kocjančič
Comment:
In the paper the alveolar affricates have a solid circle beneath them. This symbol
was unavailable to me, and I've used the open square (laminal diacritic) instead.
Prenasalisation is contrastive, and minimal pairs provided. Despite this it was not
put in the phoneme inventory. Because it is contrastive, and frequently appears in e
the transcript I have included prenasalised consonants in the phoneme inventory. N
represents a homorganic nasal preceeding the consonant.
Nasalised vowels are subphonemic - only found in loanwords, and 2 native words.
Ersu has two tones - high <ó> and low <ò>.
There are two transcripts in the JIPA paper. Here the one used for the interlinear morphemic glossing
has been used rather than the 'semi-narrow phonetic transcription'.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Standard Estonian
Contributor: Asu, Eva Liina and Teras, Pire
Comment:
JIPA articles contains notes on orthography.
The dipthongs are presented as if they are phonemic in the text, but evidence they are phonemic,
and not just sequences of vowels is not provided.
No mention is made of the use of the following symbols: raised < ̝ >, lowered <  ̞> and advanced <   ̟>.
I have treated vowels with these symbols in the transcript as allophones.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Goemai
Comment:
"Although Hellwig (2011) considers the contrast between the two types of voiceless
oral stops to be one of aspiration, other students of Goemai have analysed the contrast
differently. Wolff (1959), for example, labels the contrast as fortis vs. lenis, and Hoffman
(1975) labels it as glottalized vs. non-glattlized." p83 JIPA article

Goemai has two level tones: high <  ́ > and low < ̀ >. They combine to create HL < ̂ >
and LH < ̌ >.

Glottal stop is considered non-phonemic in the JIPA illustration, but rather a
regular phonological process. As with other languages that contain glottal stops in their transcriptions
I have not included it in the phonemic inventory.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Goizueta Basque
Contributor: Hualde, José Ignacio and Lujanbio, Oihana and Zubiri, Juan Joxe
Comment:
"In Goizueta both the position of the stress and the tonal contour or pitch-accent associated with the stressed syllable are lexically
contrastive." p123 Diacritic  ́  is a rise over the stressed vowel (a high tone), and diacritic  ̀  is falling contour (a low tone).  Above, these are presented as allophones of a single phoneme.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Hausa
Contributor: Schuh, Russell G. and Yalwa, Lawan D.
Comment:
Conventions for tones are: high tone unmarked; grave accent < ̀> for low tone;
a circumflex accent < ̂> for falling tone; the acute accent < ́> is used to mark extra-high tone.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Hebrew
Comment:
This is the Oriental dialect. Non-Oriental Hebrew has a few less phonemes than the Oriental
dialect. In the JIPA article the phoneme inventory for Oriental Hebrew was provided,
followed by transcriptions in both Oriental and non-Oriental Hebrew.
Nothing was mentioned in the text about geminate/long consonants. Because many of them are
separated by a stress symbol, they are assumed to belong to different syllables, and I have left in double consonant
symbols as in the original article.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Ibibio
Comment:
Minimal pair examples from JIPA paper.
Geminate nasals and long vowels are written with a double graph in JIPA paper. Here the length symbol has been used for
consistency across languages.
"Ibibio is a register terraced level tone language with two level tones (H)igh and (L)ow. Combinations" p107 JIPA
of the level tones from tone spreading and segment deletion result in the formation of two types of contour tones, namely,
High-Low and Low-High, which are not contrastive with each other." Also a downstep.
High is marked with < ́ >, Low is marked with < ̀ >.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Igbo
Comment: Marking of tones: < ́> indicates high tone, low tone is unmarked, and <↓ ́> indicates downstep.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Ika Igbo
Comment:
There are two major tones and a downstep: high //́/ low / ̀/ downstep /↓ ́/

Tone on nasals not specifically discussed in paper, but there are several examples of it. ‘ń’ added into phoneme inventory as allophone of ‘n’.

Geminates are written as double graph in the JIPA paper. Here the length symbol is used.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Kera
Comment:
Long vowels in original paper represented by double symbol.  Here replaced with length symbol.
Three tone types on vowels are used, which are expressed as allophones.
The symbol < ́> represents high tones; the symbol < ̄> represents mid tones; the symbol
< ̀> represents low tones.  The three tones combine within words to create 7 possible melodies
in nouns and 3 possible melodies in verbs.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Khowar
Contributor: Liljegren, Henrik and Khan, Afsar Ali
Comment:
The transcript here is of the broad transcription. A narrow transcription is also provided in the JIPA paper.
Velar nasal [ŋ] occurs in the transcription, but is not discussed in the paper nor listed as a phoneme.
Given its position in the word, my guess is that it is a homorganic nasal, and /n/ is the underlying phoneme.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Kumzari
Comment:
There is no mention in the text of many phonetic symbols that appear in the transcription.
The symbol <y> appears to be being used as a
palatal approximant rather than a vowel.  I have not included it in the consonant inventory.
The only allophones discussed in the paper are those for /ɻ/.  I have assigned all the other allophones,
to account for all sounds and therefore their status as allophones is questionable.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Lizu
Comment:
In the original paper/N/ is used to represent the homorganic nasal in contrastive prenasalized clusters.
Lizu has a "...'culminative' tonal system, in which no more than one pitch pattern is pronounced per word" p81.
Monosyllabic words have two contrastive tones marked at the beginning of the syllable:
(R) is low rising; and (F) is high falling.  In trisyllabic words there are three possible pitch patterns:
(EP) equally prominant contour; (LP) left-prominent contour; (RP) right-priminent contour.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Lower Xumi
Comment:
Minimal pair examples from JIPA.
R = rising tone; H = high tone; EP = equally-prominant contour; LP = left-prominant contour;
RP = right-prominant contour.
Glottal stop is non-phonemic.
There are two transcriptions, a semi-narrow phonetic one and an interlinear morphemic glossing one.
The interlineear morphemic glossing transcription is used here.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Luanyjang Dinka
Contributor: Remijsen, Bert and Manyang, Caguor Adong
Comment:
In the JIPA illustration vowel length is indicated by repetitions of the vowel. Here
I have used the length symbols as with other languages.

There are four tones: high < ́> low < ̀> rise < ̌> and fall < ̂>
"This toneme associates with the rightmost syllable, which is usually the only syllable."

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Lusoga Lutenga
Contributor: Nabirye, Minah and de Schryver, Gilles-Maurice and Verhoeven, Jo
Comment:
The sounds t̪ʷ, bʲ, mbʷ, mbʲ, ŋʷ, ʃ, h, fʷ, vʷ, ɱvʷ, nzʷ "...have been attested in the language, but they are very rare.
They have not been included in any of the numerical counts in this paper." (Nabirye, de Schryver & Verhoeven 2016:220)

Lusoga has four tones: H <v́>, L <v̀>, HL <v̂>, and LH <v̌>

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Luxembourgish
Comment:
The status of sounds as phonemes or allophones is somewhat confused in the article.
In the discussion some of the sounds presented in the table of consonants/ list of vowels
are said to be allophones.  Here I have followed the discussion rather than the tables in the
presentation of sounds as phonemes or allophones.
The third line of vowels are listed as foreign and rare sounds.  They are said not to historically
belong to the Luxembourgish sound system, but appear due to the multilingual habits of speakers.
Likewise the affricates in line three of the consonants are only found in English and German loanwords
respectively.

Tie bar < ͜> indicates resyllabification and voicing of voiceless obstruents across word boundaries.
Vowel [ɔ] appears in the transcription, but not mentioned anywhere in the discussion.  I have assigned it
as an allophone of /o/.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Mambay
Comment:
/ɗ/ is an implosive retroflex. /ⱱ̟/ is a bilabial flap.

Glottal stop is identified as a morpheme boundary marker by the JIPA authors, but not posited as a phoneme.
Here I have included it in the phoneme inventory, as we have no other way of representing it.

High tone [á]; low tone [à]; High-low tone [â]; downstep ↓

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Mapudungun
Contributor: Sadowsky, Scott and Painequeo, Héctor and Salamanca, Gastón and Avelino, Heriberto
Comment:
The allophones [t̺s̺] [t̺ʰ] are described as apical post-alveolar, and have a dot under
them in the original paper, which is unavailable to me.  I have therefore used the apical
diacritic instead.
No mention of nasalization, length, or labialization is made in the discussion.  Based on the broad transcription nasalized
and lengthened vowels in the narrow transcription and labialized consonants have been allocated as allophones of their non-nasalized
counterpart or non-lengthened counterparts or non-labialized counterparts.
Likewise no mention of the vowels [ɚ], [ʌ]̈ [ʉ], [ʊ̟], [ë̝ʷ], [iː], [iʷ], [i], [e], [e̝] and consonant [ʈʰ] is made,
but based on the broad transcription they have been allocated as allophones.
No mention of the retroflex click [ǃ] is made.  It has not been listed in the sounds, because it is not possible
to determine its status from the paper.
In the original paper consonant length is indicated by doubling of the letter.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Mono
Comment:
Three tones: high / ́ /, mid / ̄ / and low / ̀/.
Long sounds were not discussed in the paper. I have included them as allophones of their short counterpart.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Murcian Spanish
Contributor: Monroy, Rafael and Hernández-Campoy, Juan Manuel
Comment:
Some phonetic features present in the transcription are not discussed in the text.
This includes non-syllablic marking on vowels, and dental marking on consonants.
They are treated as allophones of their unmarked counterpart. I have treated the labio-dental
nasal as an allophone of the bilabial nasal.

There are three narrative recordings. The first an exerpt from a longer narrative by a 63 year old woman (not presented here),
and two versions of the North Wind and Sun, as told by a man and a woman. The transcribed version is that from the woman's recording.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Nara
Contributor: Dawd, Abushush and Hayward, Richard J.
Comment:
For prenasalised velar stop in the chart the palatal nasal is used. However, more logically, in the text
the velar nasal is used. Here I have assumed it should be the velar nasal.
Long sounds are written with double letters in JIPA. Here the length symbol is used.
There is a brief note that vowel-initial words are actually glottal stop initial. I assume it is non-phonemic.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Nen
Contributor: Evans, Nicholas and Miller, Julia Colleen
Comment:
Prenasalised consonants in the paper are represented by a superscript nasal followed by the oral stop.
It is not possible for me to recreate this other than the alveolar nasal.
The alveolar nasal is marked long when it is a distinct phoneme and precedes
the affricate /dʒ/, in contrast to the prenasalised affricate /ndʒ/.
The author does not mention short [ŏ] in the paper.  It has been added as an allophone of /o/.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Palula
Comment:
Vowel length in the JIPA paper is indicated by doubling of the symbol. Here I have used
the length symbol for consistency.
Aspiration is considered a property of the lexical stem. Therefore has been explained here
in terms of being an allophone of phonemes.
Palula is a pitch accent language. 1. high level (or falling) on a short vowel [ ́]
2. rising on a long vowel [ ̌] or 3. falling on a long vowel [ ̂].
Both a narrow and broad transcription are provided in th JIPA paper. I have just included the
broad transcription here.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Setswana South Africa
Contributor: Bennett, Wm. G. and Diemer, Maxine and Kerford, Justine and Probert, Tracy and Wesi, Tsholofelo
Comment:
Setswana has two phonemic tones, low < ̀ > and high < ́ >. "The tonal phonology of Setswana is complex and
tonal processes can cause high and low tones to mainfest on the same syllable, resulting in a surface rising or falling tone..." p243

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Shanghai Chinese
Comment: 5 tones: 1 (falling), 2(high rising), 3(low), 4(short high), 5(low)

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Shilluk
Contributor: Remijsen, Bert and Ayoker, Otto G. and Mills, Timothy
Comment:
There is a three way distinction between length in vowels, which in the paper is written
as single letter for short, double letter for long and triple letter for overlong.
Here I have used single symbol for short, the half-long symbol for long and the
long symbol for overlong.
Geminate consonants are indicated in the paper with a doubling of the letter.  Here I have
used the length symbol.
Tone: Low (cv́c), Mid (cv̄c), High (cv̀c), Rise (cv̌c), Fall (cv̂c), High Fall (cv̂́c),
and Late Fall (cv́c̀).  Each possible tone type is expressed on vowels which are presented
as allophones.  Consonants that take the late fall in the transcription are expressed as
allophones of the consonant phoneme.
The transcription is phonemic.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Shipibo
Contributor: Valenzuela, Pilar M. and Pinedo, Luis Márquez and Maddieson, Ian
Comment:
The glottal stop does not appear to be phonemic, but is phonetically predictable. The author
has included it in the phoneme inventory in brackets with a note about it. Because it appears in
the transcription I have included it as a phoneme, because I wasn't sure what else to do with it.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Standard Austrian German
Contributor: Moosmüller, Sylvia and Schmid, Carolin and Brandstätter, Julia
Comment:
Nothing was said about nasalised, rounded, centralised or lengthened vowels in the JIPA paper. For this reason they are added as allophones
to their non-nasalised/unrounded/non-lengthened/non-centralised counterpart.
Nothing was mentioned about syllabic nasals and laterals in the JIPA paper. They have been added in as allophones.
Nothing was mentioned in the JIPA paper about the glottal stop. It is assumed to be non-phonemic.
Nothing was said of creaky voice in the paper. Sounds in the transcript with creaky voice have been added as allophones.

Comment:
Allophonic variation of nasals and laterals and rhotics is discussed, other consonantal allophones were assigned by Louise, as were the vowel allophones.

"The glottal stop functions as an intervocalic separator only." p262 Ie. it is not a phoneme.

Nothing is mentioned in the paper on the nasal release symbol ‘ⁿ’ In line with assigning other sounds as allophones, I’ve assigned these sounds as allophones in the phoneme inventory as well.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Sumi (Sema)
Comment:
Allophone [qχ] indicates a voiceless uvular stop with a fricated release.
The transcription is phonemic, and so allophones do not appear.
There are three tones: high, marked by < ́> on the vowel; mid, which is unmarked;
and low marked by < ̀> on the vowel.
Adjacent like vowels either occur across syllable boundaries, or have an epenthetic schwa inserted,
hence in the transcription there are cases of adjacent two like vowels rather than use of the length symbol.
The sound represented by the symbol <y> in the transcription is not discussed.  Presumably
it is the palatal approximant.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Swedish
Comment:
The accent over the vowels indicates word accent.
The scwha is not discussed in the article. I assume it is an allophone of /ɛ/ based
on the orthographic version of the story.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Telugu
Comment:
In the JIPA paper the authors essentially illustrate that geminate consonants
are phonemes because they are contrastive (minimal pairs provided) with non-geminates.
However, they do not posit that they are phonemes. Since a list of those phonemes that
cannot be geminate is provided, and contrastive minimal pairs have been provided, I include
the geminate forms as separate phonemes here.

/f/ /ʃ/ and /ʂ/ only occur in borrowed vocabulary (p233)

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Temne
Contributor: Kanu, Sullay M. and Tucker, Benjamin V.
Comment:
There is dispute amongst linguists how many tones there are in Temne.  In this paper the
authors argue for two tones: High tone represented by diacritic V́ and low tone represented
by diacritic V̀.

No mention is made of the symbol <y>.  Presumably it is being used as the palatal approximant /j/.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Tilquiapan Zapotec
Comment:
Glottalization is phonemic, and marked in the article by a superscript glottal stop.
I don't have this symbol available to me, and so I have a superscript pharyngeal fricative.
Tone is phonemic with two tones - high and low, but tone is not marked in the transcription.
Vowel length is marked on vowels by doubling the vowel or through use of length symbol
in the IPA article. Here I have used the length symbol to be consistent across languages.
In several places within the the transcription the symbol <y> was used. Based on the orthography
I have either replaced this with the palatal approximant /j/ or the high front vowel /i/.
There was a random <c> in the transcription. I have assumed it is a typo and not added it.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Upper Saxon (Chemnitz dialect
Contributor: ud Dowla Khan, Sameer and Weise, Constanze
Comment:
Here schwa is placed with other phonemes, but is in fact the default vowel
for any reduced vowel, and is not considered a phoneme in its own right.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Upper Sorbian
Comment:
The phonemic status of /g/ is marginal.
/f/ and /v/ typically only appear in loan words or in complementary distribution
with opposing phonemes.
/ə/ appears in the transcript, but is not discussed anywhere in the paper.
Vowel length is said to be a realisation of secondary word stress. Here I have
included lengthened vowels as allophones of the non-lengthened variant. /ʃ/ also appears
lengthened in the transcript. Nothing is mentioned about the lengthening of consonants
in the paper.

Name: Illustrations of the IPA: Upper Xumi
Contributor: Chirkova, Katia and Chen, Yiya and Antolík, Tanja Kocjančič
Comment:
Minimal pair examples from JIPA.
"N" preceding consonants indicates prenasalisation.
R = rising tone; H = high tone; EP = Equally-prominent contour; LP = Left-prominent contour;
RP = right-prominent contour
Two transcripts are provided: a semi-narrow phonetic transcription and an interlinear morphemic glossing
transcription. Here the semi-narrow phonetic transcription has been used.
